{"cursor":"2083","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name = Awalmir native_name = background = solo_singer image = caption =\n| birth_name = birth_date = birth_place = Peshawar, British India death_date =\n| (aged 50-51) death_place = Kabul, Afghanistan genre = GhazalsClassical music\n| occupation = Singer instrument = Harmonium, guitar years_active = 1949 â 1982\n| label = Various\n}}\n\n'Ustad Awalmir' () (born 1931 â died April 24, 1982 in Kabul, Afghanistan)\nwas an Afghan composer, musician, singer and poet who wrote and sang in the\nPashto language.\n\nHe began learning music as a teen from various music teachers and began to\nperform for radio broadcasts. His first song was My Heart Has Broken To Pieces.\nAt the age of 18 he performed at the Afghan Independence Day in Kabul.\n\nHe made a breakthrough into performing on the Afghan radio station with help\nfrom Malang Jan, a local poet. Awalmir's output consists of over 250 songs as\nwell as a collection of self-composed songs. His contribution to Afghan music\nled him the honor of the title Ustad from the Ministry of Culture and\nInformation.\n\n{{Persondata \n| NAME = Awalmir ALTERNATIVE NAMES = SHORT DESCRIPTION = Afghan musician DATE OF\n| BIRTH = 1931 PLACE OF BIRTH = Peshawar, British India DATE OF DEATH = April\n| 24, 1982 PLACE OF DEATH = Kabul, Afghanistan\n}}\n","linknr":116,"url":"Awalmir","recorded":1375081290,"links":["/w/index.php?title=Awalmir&action=edit","/w/index.php?title=Awalmir&action=edit","//bits.wikimedia.org/favicon/wikipedia.ico","/w/opensearch_desc.php","//en.wikipedia.org/w/api.php?action=rsd","//creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/3.0/","/w/index.php?title=Special:RecentChanges&feed=atom","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=ext.gadget.DRN-wizard%2CReferenceTooltips%2Ccharinsert%2Cteahouse%7Cext.rtlcite%2Cwikihiero%7Cext.uls.nojs%7Cmediawiki.legacy.commonPrint%2Cshared%7Cmw.PopUpMediaTransform%7Cs